{
  "answer": "In Urdu poetry, *qismat* (قِسمت) and *taqdir* (تقدِیر, also spelled *taqdeer*) are related but not fully synonymous concepts, both orbiting the idea of \"fate.\" *Qismat* typically evokes a personal \"portion\" or \"lot in life\"—often tinged with chance, misfortune, or irony, especially in romantic or existential contexts. *Taqdir*, by contrast, carries a stronger theological weight as \"divine decree\" or predestination, implying cosmic inevitability under God's will. Poets like Ghalib and Iqbal select one over the other deliberately to nuance tone, philosophy, or imagery: *qismat* for intimate, contingent human struggles; *taqdir* for grander, ordained universality.[^1]\n\n### Ghalib\n- **Qismat example**: \"Yeh na thi hamari qismat ke visaal-e-yaar hota\" (*To be with my Beloved was not my fate*). Here, Ghalib laments unfulfilled love as a cruel personal allotment, underscoring the lover's passive endurance of romantic irony rather than divine mandate.[^2]\n- **Taqdir example**: \"Us mein kuch shaaiba-e-khoobi-e-taqdeer bhi tha\" (*In that ruin, there was also a shadow of a kinder fate*). In a ghazal on delayed union and self-destruction, Ghalib invokes *taqdir* to hint at a subtle divine benevolence amid calamity, elevating personal ruin to a providential design.[^3]\n\nGhalib (19th century) favors *qismat* (~20+ instances across his *Diwan*) for ghazal introspection on love's caprice, reserving *taqdir* (~few instances) for ironic consolation in suffering.\n\n### Iqbal\n- **Qismat example**: \"Lekin meri kutia ki na jaagi kabhi qismat\" (*But my poor hut has never been so blessed*). In the fable \"Ek Makra aur Makhi\" (A Spider and a Fly), the spider blames his *qismat* for perpetual isolation—a mundane, creaturely bad luck in a satirical nod to human scheming.[^4]\n- **Taqdir example**: \"Taare mast-e-sharaab-e-taqdeer\" (*The stars are drunk on the wine of their Fate*). In \"Insaan\" (Man), Iqbal uses *taqdir* for celestial bodies chained in heaven's prison, symbolizing humanity's entrapment in God's cosmic order amid existential thirst.[^5]\n\nIqbal (20th century) deploys *qismat* (~10+ instances) in fables or personal plaints for motivational critique of passivity, while *taqdir* (~few instances) suits his philosophical visions of divine purpose and self-realization.\n\n[^1]: This distinction aligns with classical Urdu/Persian usage; the corpus shows *qismat* dominating personal contexts (e.g., 30 hits vs. 8 for *taqdeer*), with deliberate toggling per poet's intent.\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 204 (*Yeh na thi hamari qismat ke visaal-e-yaar hota*), translation (/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/204-yeh-na-thi-hamari-qismat-ke-visaal-e-yaar-hota/translation/#p-e43078).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 73 (*Hui taakhir to kuch baais-e-taakhir bhi tha*), translation (/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/73-hui-taakhir-to-kuch-baais-e-taakhir-bhi-tha/translation/#p-c45bbd).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 20 (*Ek Makra aur Makhi*), translation (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/20-ek-makra-aur-makhi/translation/#p-558da0).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 14 (*Insaan*), translation (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/#p-3ebd11).",
